{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01XckfNxaFSdevMqaooMrtgP","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have the complete picture. Let me compile all findings into the comprehensive JSON analysis:\n\n---\n\nHere is the comprehensive impact analysis of gRPC-Go PR #1157 (metadata incoming/outgoing context separation) on the etcd codebase:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"api_changes\": {\n    \"removed\": [\n      \"func FromContext(ctx context.Context) (md MD, ok bool)  — wrapper for FromIncomingContext, present in grpc-go ≤ v1.4.0, ABSENT by v1.14.0\",\n      \"func NewContext(ctx context.Context, md MD) context.Context  — wrapper for NewOutgoingContext, present in grpc-go ≤ v1.4.0, ABSENT by v1.14.0\"\n    ],\n    \"added\": [\n      \"func NewIncomingContext(ctx context.Context, md MD) context.Context  — stores MD under mdIncomingKey{}; used server-side by gRPC runtime\",\n      \"func NewOutgoingContext(ctx context.Context, md MD) context.Context  — stores MD under mdOutgoingKey{}; used client-side\",\n      \"func FromIncomingContext(ctx context.Context) (MD, bool)  — reads from mdIncomingKey{}\",\n      \"func FromOutgoingContext(ctx context.Context) (MD, bool)  — reads from mdOutgoingKey{}\",\n      \"func AppendToOutgoingContext(ctx context.Context, kv ...string) context.Context  — added in later releases\",\n      \"func ValueFromIncomingContext(ctx context.Context, key string) []string  — added in later releases\"\n    ],\n    \"description\": \"PR #1157 introduced separate context keys for incoming (server-received) and outgoing (client-sent) metadata, splitting the previously unified context key into mdIncomingKey{} and mdOutgoingKey{}. Before the split, a single context key held all metadata, so FromContext read whatever was put in by both the gRPC runtime (incoming) and the user (outgoing). After the split, incoming metadata (populated by the gRPC server transport) lives under mdIncomingKey{}, and outgoing metadata (populated by the client before a call) lives under mdOutgoingKey{}. The deprecated shims FromContext→FromIncomingContext and NewContext→NewOutgoingContext were present in v1.4.0 but completely removed by v1.14.0. The critical behavioral consequence: any code inside a gRPC server handler that calls FromOutgoingContext(stream.Context()) will ALWAYS return ok=false because the server transport populates only the incoming key, never the outgoing key. This is a silent runtime failure — the code compiles but the metadata is silently dropped.\"\n  },\n\n  \"affected_files\": [\n    {\n      \"path\": \"auth/store.go  (coreos/etcd era, vendored in k8s v1.7.3 and v1.9.1)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/coreos/etcd  (via github.com/sg-evals/kubernetes--v1.7.3 and kubernetes--v1.9.1)\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromContext\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"compile_error\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": false,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"None — reads incoming token for auth only (AuthInfoFromCtx), not forwarded to outgoing\",\n      \"severity\": \"high\",\n      \"notes\": \"Function AuthInfoFromCtx calls metadata.FromContext(ctx) to extract the auth token. When grpc-go removes FromContext, this becomes a compile error. The fix is metadata.FromIncomingContext(ctx). Present in k8s v1.7.3 and v1.9.1 vendor trees. By etcd v3.3.0 this was already migrated to metadata.FromIncomingContext.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"etcdserver/api/v3rpc/interceptor.go  (coreos/etcd era, vendored in k8s v1.7.3 and v1.9.1)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/coreos/etcd  (via github.com/sg-evals/kubernetes--v1.7.3 and kubernetes--v1.9.1)\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromContext\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"compile_error\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": false,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"None — reads incoming metadata in server interceptor to check MetadataRequireLeaderKey\",\n      \"severity\": \"high\",\n      \"notes\": \"Two call sites: newUnaryInterceptor checks leader key from incoming metadata, newStreamInterceptor does the same for streams. Both call metadata.FromContext(ctx) / metadata.FromContext(ss.Context()). By etcd v3.3.0 both were migrated to FromIncomingContext. Compile error when grpc-go removes FromContext.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"proxy/grpcproxy/watch.go  (coreos/etcd era, vendored in k8s v1.9.1)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/coreos/etcd  (via github.com/sg-evals/kubernetes--v1.9.1)\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromContext\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"compile_error\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": false,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"Reads stream metadata to check MetadataRequireLeaderKey inside a server handler — but uses the old FromContext which pre-split read both directions\",\n      \"severity\": \"critical\",\n      \"notes\": \"metadata.FromContext(stream.Context()) inside the Watch server-stream handler. After PR #1157: grpc-go stores incoming metadata under mdIncomingKey{}, so this should become FromIncomingContext — but etcd v3.3.0 through latest instead migrated it to FromOutgoingContext (see next entry), which is the wrong replacement. This migration introduced a silent regression.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"proxy/grpcproxy/watch.go  (etcd v3.3.0 through latest / d89978e8)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.3.0, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.4.3, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--d89978e8 (v3.5.17+)\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromOutgoingContext  (wrong replacement for pre-split FromContext in a server handler)\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"runtime_behavior\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": true,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"Server-side handler calls metadata.FromOutgoingContext(stream.Context()) to read MetadataRequireLeaderKey. In a gRPC server handler, stream.Context() has metadata in mdIncomingKey{}, NOT mdOutgoingKey{}. FromOutgoingContext always returns ok=false here. The require-leader enforcement in the Watch proxy is therefore completely silently bypassed.\",\n      \"severity\": \"critical\",\n      \"notes\": \"Code: `if md, ok := metadata.FromOutgoingContext(stream.Context()); ok { v := md[rpctypes.MetadataRequireLeaderKey] ...}`. The block never executes because ok is always false on the server side. The require-leader feature of the grpc proxy silently fails: even if a client sends MetadataRequireLeaderKey, the proxy will not enforce it. Correct fix: use metadata.FromIncomingContext(stream.Context()). Present in v3.3.0, v3.4.3, v3.4.7, v3.5.x, and latest (d89978e8).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"proxy/grpcproxy/lease.go  (etcd v3.3.0 through latest / d89978e8)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.3.0, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.4.3, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--d89978e8\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromOutgoingContext  (wrong replacement for pre-split FromContext in a server handler)\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"runtime_behavior\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": true,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"Same pattern as proxy/grpcproxy/watch.go: server handler calls metadata.FromOutgoingContext(stream.Context()) to check MetadataRequireLeaderKey for LeaseKeepAlive streams.\",\n      \"severity\": \"critical\",\n      \"notes\": \"Code: `if md, ok := metadata.FromOutgoingContext(stream.Context()); ok { v := md[rpctypes.MetadataRequireLeaderKey] ...}`. Always ok=false in server context. LeaseKeepAlive's require-leader enforcement is silently bypassed in the grpc proxy. Same fix needed: FromIncomingContext.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"auth/store.go  (etcd v3.3.0 through latest)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.3.0, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.4.3, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--d89978e8\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromIncomingContext\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"deprecation\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": false,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"None — correctly reads incoming token for authentication\",\n      \"severity\": \"low\",\n      \"notes\": \"AuthInfoFromCtx correctly uses FromIncomingContext to extract auth token from server-side context. This is the correct post-PR-#1157 API. No issue here — included for completeness.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"etcdserver/api/v3rpc/interceptor.go  (etcd v3.3.0 through latest)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.3.0, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.4.3, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--d89978e8\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromIncomingContext\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"deprecation\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": false,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"None — correctly reads incoming metadata in server interceptors for leader key, API version, etc.\",\n      \"severity\": \"low\",\n      \"notes\": \"Correctly uses FromIncomingContext in both unary and stream server interceptors. No issue. Included for completeness.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"proxy/grpcproxy/util.go  (v3.3.0 through latest)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.3.0, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.4.3, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--d89978e8\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromIncomingContext\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"deprecation\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": false,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"Reads auth token from incoming context in getAuthTokenFromClient, then passes it through a per-RPC credential — does NOT naively forward the raw metadata MD, uses PerRPCCredentials instead.\",\n      \"severity\": \"low\",\n      \"notes\": \"getAuthTokenFromClient correctly uses FromIncomingContext to extract token on server side. Auth forwarding goes via proxyTokenCredential/PerRPCCredentials which is the proper pattern. No issue.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"clientv3/client.go  →  client/v3/ctx.go  (all versions)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/coreos/etcd (old: NewContext), github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.3.0+ (NewOutgoingContext)\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.NewContext  (coreos/etcd era)\", \"metadata.NewOutgoingContext  (v3.3.0+)\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"compile_error  (for coreos/etcd era only)\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": false,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"Client-side context creation for WithRequireLeader — places metadata in outgoing context before making a gRPC call. Correct usage.\",\n      \"severity\": \"high  (compile error for coreos era), low  (v3.3.0+ already correct)\",\n      \"notes\": \"In coreos/etcd: metadata.NewContext(ctx, md) sets the require-leader key. NewContext was a deprecated shim for NewOutgoingContext that was removed. Fix: replace with metadata.NewOutgoingContext. By v3.3.0, etcd already uses NewOutgoingContext correctly.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"clientv3/lease.go  →  client/v3/lease.go  (all versions)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.3.0, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.4.3, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--d89978e8\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromOutgoingContext\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"deprecation\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": false,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"Client-side code reading outgoing context to group keepalive channels by require-leader key. Correct usage — this is client-side context.\",\n      \"severity\": \"low\",\n      \"notes\": \"closeRequireLeader iterates client-held contexts and reads FromOutgoingContext to find which leases have require-leader. Correct — these are client contexts populated by the user, not server-received contexts.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"clientv3/watch.go  →  client/v3/watch.go  (all versions)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.3.0, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.4.3, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--d89978e8\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromOutgoingContext\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"deprecation\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": false,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"Client-side: streamKeyFromCtx reads outgoing metadata to compute a stream dedup key. Correct usage.\",\n      \"severity\": \"low\",\n      \"notes\": \"streamKeyFromCtx is a client-side function that distinguishes watch streams by their outgoing context metadata. Correct use of FromOutgoingContext.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"server/etcdserver/cluster_util.go  (latest / d89978e8)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/sg-evals/etcd--d89978e8\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromIncomingContext\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"deprecation\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": true,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"Reads auth token from gRPC incoming metadata (FromIncomingContext) and forwards it as an HTTP Authorization header when proxying member promote requests over HTTP. This is intentional cross-protocol forwarding.\",\n      \"severity\": \"medium\",\n      \"notes\": \"promoteMember reads incoming gRPC metadata to extract token fields (TokenFieldNameGRPC and TokenFieldNameSwagger) and sets them as HTTP headers. This is correct use of FromIncomingContext but is technically metadata forwarding between protocols. Any change to incoming metadata handling would silently drop the auth token forwarding.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"pkg/grpctesting/recorder.go  (latest / d89978e8)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/sg-evals/etcd--d89978e8\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromIncomingContext\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"deprecation\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": false,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"Test helper records incoming metadata for test assertions\",\n      \"severity\": \"low\",\n      \"notes\": \"Test infrastructure only; reads FromIncomingContext to record observed metadata. Correct usage.\"\n    }\n  ],\n\n  \"critical_forwarding_files\": [\n    \"proxy/grpcproxy/watch.go  — uses FromOutgoingContext in server handler (should be FromIncomingContext), silently never reads MetadataRequireLeaderKey\",\n    \"proxy/grpcproxy/lease.go  — same bug as watch.go for LeaseKeepAlive streams\",\n    \"server/etcdserver/cluster_util.go  — reads FromIncomingContext and forwards token as HTTP header (correct but fragile)\"\n  ],\n\n  \"summary\": {\n    \"total_affected\": 12,\n    \"compile_errors\": 4,\n    \"runtime_behavior_changes\": 2,\n    \"critical_forwarding\": 2,\n    \"description_of_compile_errors\": \"All 4 compile errors are in the pre-v3.3.0 coreos/etcd codebase: auth/store.go (metadata.FromContext), etcdserver/api/v3rpc/interceptor.go (2x metadata.FromContext), and clientv3/client.go (metadata.NewContext). These were fixed in the v3.3.0 migration to the new API.\",\n    \"description_of_critical_bugs\": \"The two critical runtime bugs are in proxy/grpcproxy/watch.go and proxy/grpcproxy/lease.go. They were INTRODUCED when migrating from the old metadata.FromContext to the new API: developers incorrectly chose metadata.FromOutgoingContext instead of metadata.FromIncomingContext for server-side stream contexts. Because metadata.FromOutgoingContext always returns ok=false in a gRPC server handler (the gRPC transport only populates the incoming key), the MetadataRequireLeaderKey check in the Watch and LeaseKeepAlive gRPC proxy handlers silently never executes. This means the grpc proxy does not enforce the require-leader constraint for watch and lease keepalive streams, a behavior regression that persists from v3.3.0 through the latest (d89978e8 / v3.5.17+).\",\n    \"grpc_go_version_of_removal\": \"FromContext and NewContext were present (as deprecated wrappers) in grpc-go v1.4.0 and fully removed by v1.14.0. The removal happened between these two versions — PR #1157 is the commit that introduced the key split and added the deprecated shims; the shims were then removed in a follow-up cleanup (between v1.4.0 and v1.14.0).\"\n  }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Key Findings Summary\n\n**The grpc-go PR #1157 change** split a single unified metadata context key into two separate keys:\n- `mdIncomingKey{}` — populated by the gRPC server transport when a request arrives; read via `FromIncomingContext`\n- `mdOutgoingKey{}` — populated by client code before making a call; read via `FromOutgoingContext`\n\nThe old `FromContext` / `NewContext` functions were deprecated shims (present in v1.4.0) and fully **removed by v1.14.0**, causing compile errors in pre-v3.3.0 coreos/etcd.\n\n**The most serious consequence** is not the compile errors (which are obvious and were fixed in v3.3.0) but a **silent runtime regression** introduced during that fix. In `proxy/grpcproxy/watch.go` and `proxy/grpcproxy/lease.go`, developers migrated from the old `FromContext` to `FromOutgoingContext` instead of `FromIncomingContext`. Inside a gRPC server handler, `stream.Context()` always has metadata under `mdIncomingKey{}` (never `mdOutgoingKey{}`), so `FromOutgoingContext` always returns `ok=false`. The result: the `MetadataRequireLeaderKey` require-leader enforcement in the **Watch and LeaseKeepAlive gRPC proxy** is completely silently bypassed in every version from **v3.3.0 through the latest (v3.5.17+)**. The correct fix in both files is to use `metadata.FromIncomingContext(stream.Context())`."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a2aa17c397b5ff39d (use SendMessage with to: 'a2aa17c397b5ff39d' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 56441\ntool_uses: 57\nduration_ms: 335439</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9c6a61d1-0fa0-43c6-80f7-1a961d909727","uuid":"6ea8b301-15c1-4096-a307-a5fc246a835a","timestamp":"2026-04-01T01:26:58.547Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"\nAnalyze the impact of the gRPC-Go metadata context separation change on the etcd codebase.\n\n## Tasks\n\n### 1. Find the grpc-go PR #1157 changes in metadata.go\nUse `mcp__sourcegraph__read_file` to read the current grpc-go metadata package:\n- Repo: `github.com/grpc/grpc-go`\n- File: `metadata/metadata.go`\n\nAlso use `mcp__sourcegraph__commit_search` or `mcp__sourcegraph__diff_search` to find the changes from PR #1157 in grpc-go. Try searching for commits related to \"metadata FromIncomingContext\" or \"metadata context separation\".\n\n### 2. Find all etcd files using old grpc metadata API\nUse `mcp__sourcegraph__keyword_search` to find all files in etcd repos that use:\n- `metadata.FromContext`\n- `metadata.NewContext`\n- `metadata.FromIncomingContext`\n- `metadata.FromOutgoingContext`\n- `metadata.NewOutgoingContext`\n\nSearch in: `github.com/etcd-io/etcd` or `github.com/coreos/etcd`\n\n### 3. For each affected file, determine:\n- Which old API functions it uses\n- Whether it's doing metadata forwarding (reading incoming metadata and adding to outgoing context - this is the most dangerous pattern)\n- Breakage type: compile error (old function removed) vs runtime (silent metadata drop)\n\n## MCP Tool Usage\nUse these tools:\n- `mcp__sourcegraph__read_file` with `{\"repo\": \"github.com/grpc/grpc-go\", \"file_path\": \"metadata/metadata.go\"}` (no revision needed for latest)\n- `mcp__sourcegraph__keyword_search` with `{\"query\": \"metadata.FromContext repo:github.com/etcd-io/etcd\"}`\n- `mcp__sourcegraph__keyword_search` with `{\"query\": \"metadata.NewContext repo:github.com/etcd-io/etcd\"}`\n- `mcp__sourcegraph__diff_search` or `mcp__sourcegraph__commit_search` to find the PR #1157 changes\n\n## Output\nReturn a comprehensive JSON structure with:\n```json\n{\n  \"api_changes\": {\n    \"removed\": [\"list of removed/renamed functions with signatures\"],\n    \"added\": [\"new replacement functions with signatures\"],\n    \"description\": \"summary of the breaking change\"\n  },\n  \"affected_files\": [\n    {\n      \"path\": \"relative/path/in/etcd\",\n      \"repo\": \"full repo path\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromContext\", etc],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"compile_error|runtime_behavior|deprecation\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": true/false,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"description if forwarding\",\n      \"severity\": \"critical|high|medium|low\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"critical_forwarding_files\": [\"list of files doing metadata forwarding\"],\n  \"summary\": {\n    \"total_affected\": N,\n    \"compile_errors\": N,\n    \"runtime_behavior_changes\": N,\n    \"critical_forwarding\": N\n  }\n}\n```\n\nBe thorough - missing files means incomplete impact analysis. Search multiple etcd repos (etcd-io/etcd, coreos/etcd).\n","agentId":"a2aa17c397b5ff39d","agentType":"general-purpose","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have the complete picture. Let me compile all findings into the comprehensive JSON analysis:\n\n---\n\nHere is the comprehensive impact analysis of gRPC-Go PR #1157 (metadata incoming/outgoing context separation) on the etcd codebase:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"api_changes\": {\n    \"removed\": [\n      \"func FromContext(ctx context.Context) (md MD, ok bool)  — wrapper for FromIncomingContext, present in grpc-go ≤ v1.4.0, ABSENT by v1.14.0\",\n      \"func NewContext(ctx context.Context, md MD) context.Context  — wrapper for NewOutgoingContext, present in grpc-go ≤ v1.4.0, ABSENT by v1.14.0\"\n    ],\n    \"added\": [\n      \"func NewIncomingContext(ctx context.Context, md MD) context.Context  — stores MD under mdIncomingKey{}; used server-side by gRPC runtime\",\n      \"func NewOutgoingContext(ctx context.Context, md MD) context.Context  — stores MD under mdOutgoingKey{}; used client-side\",\n      \"func FromIncomingContext(ctx context.Context) (MD, bool)  — reads from mdIncomingKey{}\",\n      \"func FromOutgoingContext(ctx context.Context) (MD, bool)  — reads from mdOutgoingKey{}\",\n      \"func AppendToOutgoingContext(ctx context.Context, kv ...string) context.Context  — added in later releases\",\n      \"func ValueFromIncomingContext(ctx context.Context, key string) []string  — added in later releases\"\n    ],\n    \"description\": \"PR #1157 introduced separate context keys for incoming (server-received) and outgoing (client-sent) metadata, splitting the previously unified context key into mdIncomingKey{} and mdOutgoingKey{}. Before the split, a single context key held all metadata, so FromContext read whatever was put in by both the gRPC runtime (incoming) and the user (outgoing). After the split, incoming metadata (populated by the gRPC server transport) lives under mdIncomingKey{}, and outgoing metadata (populated by the client before a call) lives under mdOutgoingKey{}. The deprecated shims FromContext→FromIncomingContext and NewContext→NewOutgoingContext were present in v1.4.0 but completely removed by v1.14.0. The critical behavioral consequence: any code inside a gRPC server handler that calls FromOutgoingContext(stream.Context()) will ALWAYS return ok=false because the server transport populates only the incoming key, never the outgoing key. This is a silent runtime failure — the code compiles but the metadata is silently dropped.\"\n  },\n\n  \"affected_files\": [\n    {\n      \"path\": \"auth/store.go  (coreos/etcd era, vendored in k8s v1.7.3 and v1.9.1)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/coreos/etcd  (via github.com/sg-evals/kubernetes--v1.7.3 and kubernetes--v1.9.1)\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromContext\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"compile_error\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": false,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"None — reads incoming token for auth only (AuthInfoFromCtx), not forwarded to outgoing\",\n      \"severity\": \"high\",\n      \"notes\": \"Function AuthInfoFromCtx calls metadata.FromContext(ctx) to extract the auth token. When grpc-go removes FromContext, this becomes a compile error. The fix is metadata.FromIncomingContext(ctx). Present in k8s v1.7.3 and v1.9.1 vendor trees. By etcd v3.3.0 this was already migrated to metadata.FromIncomingContext.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"etcdserver/api/v3rpc/interceptor.go  (coreos/etcd era, vendored in k8s v1.7.3 and v1.9.1)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/coreos/etcd  (via github.com/sg-evals/kubernetes--v1.7.3 and kubernetes--v1.9.1)\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromContext\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"compile_error\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": false,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"None — reads incoming metadata in server interceptor to check MetadataRequireLeaderKey\",\n      \"severity\": \"high\",\n      \"notes\": \"Two call sites: newUnaryInterceptor checks leader key from incoming metadata, newStreamInterceptor does the same for streams. Both call metadata.FromContext(ctx) / metadata.FromContext(ss.Context()). By etcd v3.3.0 both were migrated to FromIncomingContext. Compile error when grpc-go removes FromContext.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"proxy/grpcproxy/watch.go  (coreos/etcd era, vendored in k8s v1.9.1)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/coreos/etcd  (via github.com/sg-evals/kubernetes--v1.9.1)\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromContext\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"compile_error\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": false,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"Reads stream metadata to check MetadataRequireLeaderKey inside a server handler — but uses the old FromContext which pre-split read both directions\",\n      \"severity\": \"critical\",\n      \"notes\": \"metadata.FromContext(stream.Context()) inside the Watch server-stream handler. After PR #1157: grpc-go stores incoming metadata under mdIncomingKey{}, so this should become FromIncomingContext — but etcd v3.3.0 through latest instead migrated it to FromOutgoingContext (see next entry), which is the wrong replacement. This migration introduced a silent regression.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"proxy/grpcproxy/watch.go  (etcd v3.3.0 through latest / d89978e8)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.3.0, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.4.3, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--d89978e8 (v3.5.17+)\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromOutgoingContext  (wrong replacement for pre-split FromContext in a server handler)\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"runtime_behavior\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": true,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"Server-side handler calls metadata.FromOutgoingContext(stream.Context()) to read MetadataRequireLeaderKey. In a gRPC server handler, stream.Context() has metadata in mdIncomingKey{}, NOT mdOutgoingKey{}. FromOutgoingContext always returns ok=false here. The require-leader enforcement in the Watch proxy is therefore completely silently bypassed.\",\n      \"severity\": \"critical\",\n      \"notes\": \"Code: `if md, ok := metadata.FromOutgoingContext(stream.Context()); ok { v := md[rpctypes.MetadataRequireLeaderKey] ...}`. The block never executes because ok is always false on the server side. The require-leader feature of the grpc proxy silently fails: even if a client sends MetadataRequireLeaderKey, the proxy will not enforce it. Correct fix: use metadata.FromIncomingContext(stream.Context()). Present in v3.3.0, v3.4.3, v3.4.7, v3.5.x, and latest (d89978e8).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"proxy/grpcproxy/lease.go  (etcd v3.3.0 through latest / d89978e8)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.3.0, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.4.3, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--d89978e8\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromOutgoingContext  (wrong replacement for pre-split FromContext in a server handler)\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"runtime_behavior\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": true,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"Same pattern as proxy/grpcproxy/watch.go: server handler calls metadata.FromOutgoingContext(stream.Context()) to check MetadataRequireLeaderKey for LeaseKeepAlive streams.\",\n      \"severity\": \"critical\",\n      \"notes\": \"Code: `if md, ok := metadata.FromOutgoingContext(stream.Context()); ok { v := md[rpctypes.MetadataRequireLeaderKey] ...}`. Always ok=false in server context. LeaseKeepAlive's require-leader enforcement is silently bypassed in the grpc proxy. Same fix needed: FromIncomingContext.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"auth/store.go  (etcd v3.3.0 through latest)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.3.0, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.4.3, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--d89978e8\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromIncomingContext\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"deprecation\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": false,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"None — correctly reads incoming token for authentication\",\n      \"severity\": \"low\",\n      \"notes\": \"AuthInfoFromCtx correctly uses FromIncomingContext to extract auth token from server-side context. This is the correct post-PR-#1157 API. No issue here — included for completeness.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"etcdserver/api/v3rpc/interceptor.go  (etcd v3.3.0 through latest)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.3.0, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.4.3, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--d89978e8\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromIncomingContext\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"deprecation\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": false,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"None — correctly reads incoming metadata in server interceptors for leader key, API version, etc.\",\n      \"severity\": \"low\",\n      \"notes\": \"Correctly uses FromIncomingContext in both unary and stream server interceptors. No issue. Included for completeness.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"proxy/grpcproxy/util.go  (v3.3.0 through latest)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.3.0, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.4.3, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--d89978e8\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromIncomingContext\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"deprecation\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": false,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"Reads auth token from incoming context in getAuthTokenFromClient, then passes it through a per-RPC credential — does NOT naively forward the raw metadata MD, uses PerRPCCredentials instead.\",\n      \"severity\": \"low\",\n      \"notes\": \"getAuthTokenFromClient correctly uses FromIncomingContext to extract token on server side. Auth forwarding goes via proxyTokenCredential/PerRPCCredentials which is the proper pattern. No issue.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"clientv3/client.go  →  client/v3/ctx.go  (all versions)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/coreos/etcd (old: NewContext), github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.3.0+ (NewOutgoingContext)\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.NewContext  (coreos/etcd era)\", \"metadata.NewOutgoingContext  (v3.3.0+)\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"compile_error  (for coreos/etcd era only)\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": false,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"Client-side context creation for WithRequireLeader — places metadata in outgoing context before making a gRPC call. Correct usage.\",\n      \"severity\": \"high  (compile error for coreos era), low  (v3.3.0+ already correct)\",\n      \"notes\": \"In coreos/etcd: metadata.NewContext(ctx, md) sets the require-leader key. NewContext was a deprecated shim for NewOutgoingContext that was removed. Fix: replace with metadata.NewOutgoingContext. By v3.3.0, etcd already uses NewOutgoingContext correctly.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"clientv3/lease.go  →  client/v3/lease.go  (all versions)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.3.0, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.4.3, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--d89978e8\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromOutgoingContext\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"deprecation\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": false,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"Client-side code reading outgoing context to group keepalive channels by require-leader key. Correct usage — this is client-side context.\",\n      \"severity\": \"low\",\n      \"notes\": \"closeRequireLeader iterates client-held contexts and reads FromOutgoingContext to find which leases have require-leader. Correct — these are client contexts populated by the user, not server-received contexts.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"clientv3/watch.go  →  client/v3/watch.go  (all versions)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.3.0, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--v3.4.3, github.com/sg-evals/etcd--d89978e8\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromOutgoingContext\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"deprecation\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": false,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"Client-side: streamKeyFromCtx reads outgoing metadata to compute a stream dedup key. Correct usage.\",\n      \"severity\": \"low\",\n      \"notes\": \"streamKeyFromCtx is a client-side function that distinguishes watch streams by their outgoing context metadata. Correct use of FromOutgoingContext.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"server/etcdserver/cluster_util.go  (latest / d89978e8)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/sg-evals/etcd--d89978e8\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromIncomingContext\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"deprecation\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": true,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"Reads auth token from gRPC incoming metadata (FromIncomingContext) and forwards it as an HTTP Authorization header when proxying member promote requests over HTTP. This is intentional cross-protocol forwarding.\",\n      \"severity\": \"medium\",\n      \"notes\": \"promoteMember reads incoming gRPC metadata to extract token fields (TokenFieldNameGRPC and TokenFieldNameSwagger) and sets them as HTTP headers. This is correct use of FromIncomingContext but is technically metadata forwarding between protocols. Any change to incoming metadata handling would silently drop the auth token forwarding.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"pkg/grpctesting/recorder.go  (latest / d89978e8)\",\n      \"repo\": \"github.com/sg-evals/etcd--d89978e8\",\n      \"old_api_uses\": [\"metadata.FromIncomingContext\"],\n      \"breakage_type\": \"deprecation\",\n      \"is_metadata_forwarding\": false,\n      \"forwarding_pattern\": \"Test helper records incoming metadata for test assertions\",\n      \"severity\": \"low\",\n      \"notes\": \"Test infrastructure only; reads FromIncomingContext to record observed metadata. Correct usage.\"\n    }\n  ],\n\n  \"critical_forwarding_files\": [\n    \"proxy/grpcproxy/watch.go  — uses FromOutgoingContext in server handler (should be FromIncomingContext), silently never reads MetadataRequireLeaderKey\",\n    \"proxy/grpcproxy/lease.go  — same bug as watch.go for LeaseKeepAlive streams\",\n    \"server/etcdserver/cluster_util.go  — reads FromIncomingContext and forwards token as HTTP header (correct but fragile)\"\n  ],\n\n  \"summary\": {\n    \"total_affected\": 12,\n    \"compile_errors\": 4,\n    \"runtime_behavior_changes\": 2,\n    \"critical_forwarding\": 2,\n    \"description_of_compile_errors\": \"All 4 compile errors are in the pre-v3.3.0 coreos/etcd codebase: auth/store.go (metadata.FromContext), etcdserver/api/v3rpc/interceptor.go (2x metadata.FromContext), and clientv3/client.go (metadata.NewContext). These were fixed in the v3.3.0 migration to the new API.\",\n    \"description_of_critical_bugs\": \"The two critical runtime bugs are in proxy/grpcproxy/watch.go and proxy/grpcproxy/lease.go. They were INTRODUCED when migrating from the old metadata.FromContext to the new API: developers incorrectly chose metadata.FromOutgoingContext instead of metadata.FromIncomingContext for server-side stream contexts. Because metadata.FromOutgoingContext always returns ok=false in a gRPC server handler (the gRPC transport only populates the incoming key), the MetadataRequireLeaderKey check in the Watch and LeaseKeepAlive gRPC proxy handlers silently never executes. This means the grpc proxy does not enforce the require-leader constraint for watch and lease keepalive streams, a behavior regression that persists from v3.3.0 through the latest (d89978e8 / v3.5.17+).\",\n    \"grpc_go_version_of_removal\": \"FromContext and NewContext were present (as deprecated wrappers) in grpc-go v1.4.0 and fully removed by v1.14.0. The removal happened between these two versions — PR #1157 is the commit that introduced the key split and added the deprecated shims; the shims were then removed in a follow-up cleanup (between v1.4.0 and v1.14.0).\"\n  }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Key Findings Summary\n\n**The grpc-go PR #1157 change** split a single unified metadata context key into two separate keys:\n- `mdIncomingKey{}` — populated by the gRPC server transport when a request arrives; read via `FromIncomingContext`\n- `mdOutgoingKey{}` — populated by client code before making a call; read via `FromOutgoingContext`\n\nThe old `FromContext` / `NewContext` functions were deprecated shims (present in v1.4.0) and fully **removed by v1.14.0**, causing compile errors in pre-v3.3.0 coreos/etcd.\n\n**The most serious consequence** is not the compile errors (which are obvious and were fixed in v3.3.0) but a **silent runtime regression** introduced during that fix. In `proxy/grpcproxy/watch.go` and `proxy/grpcproxy/lease.go`, developers migrated from the old `FromContext` to `FromOutgoingContext` instead of `FromIncomingContext`. Inside a gRPC server handler, `stream.Context()` always has metadata under `mdIncomingKey{}` (never `mdOutgoingKey{}`), so `FromOutgoingContext` always returns `ok=false`. The result: the `MetadataRequireLeaderKey` require-leader enforcement in the **Watch and LeaseKeepAlive gRPC proxy** is completely silently bypassed in every version from **v3.3.0 through the latest (v3.5.17+)**. The correct fix in both files is to use `metadata.FromIncomingContext(stream.Context())`."}],"totalDurationMs":335439,"totalTokens":56441,"totalToolUseCount":57,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1313,"cache_read_input_tokens":50094,"output_tokens":5033,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1313},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
